ce:section.ce:para:
Firstly, the feasibility of the proposed method to detect individual DOX, CTC and TC in real samples containing only one of them was evaluated by using tap water and pork samples which were pretreated according to the procedures described in the experimental section in detail. Then the pretreated samples were spiked with DOX, CTC and TC at different concentrations (2.50, 5.00, 7.50 μM), respectively, followed by recovery tests performed with the proposed method. The recoveries for DOX are in the range of 96.00–102.80% with RSD below 4.09% in tap water samples, and 98.23–101.52% with RSD being less than 5.49% in pork sample (Table 1
                        ). And CTC were recovered for 99.73–100.93% with RSD being less than 3.17% from tap water sample and for 98.56–104.43% with RSD below 4.98% from pork sample (Table 2
                        ). The recoveries for TC were obtained in the range of 100.25–107.12% with RSD below 3.55% in tap water sample and 97.80–103.47% with RSD of less than 3.72% in pork samples, respectively (Table 3
                        ). The CDs based methods can detect TCs accurately when the samples containing only one kind of TCs.

Then, the feasibility of the proposed method to differentiate and quantitatively detect DOX and CTC in real samples was evaluated by using tap water and pork samples containing the mixture of DOX, CTC and TC. Then the pretreated tap and pork samples were spiked with the mixtures of DOX, CTC and TC according to the flowing combinations, 2.50:2.50:2.50 μM, 5.00:5.00:5.00 μM and 7.50:7.50:7.50 μM. And DOX and CTC were discriminated and quantitatively detected with the proposed methods. In order to avoid the IFE at 390 nm(Fig. 6A), the detection method of DOX in the mixture were developed by using the response signal only at 511 nm. And the linear equations are F/F0 = 0.98201c + 0.95646 (R2 = 0.987) in the range of 0.2–2.0 μM and F/F0 = 0.29187c + 2.42973 (R2 = 0.980) in the range of 2.0–10.0 μM (Fig. 6
                        B). DOX could be recovered from the tap water samples containing the mixtures of TCs for 95.53–104.63% with RSD below 5.45% and from the pork samples containing the mixtures of TCs for 94.09–97.70% with RSD of less than 7.17% (Table 4
                        ). The recoveries for CTC in the tap water samples containing the mixtures of TCs are in the range of 97.07–103.09% with RSD below 5.26% and in the pork samples containing the mixtures of TCs are in the range of 93.45–96.94% with RSD of less than 6.27% (Table 5
                        ). Therefore, the proposed method can differentiate and quantitatively detect DOX and CTC in real samples containing the mixture of DOX, CTC and TC without interferences between them.
